<font color="#FF0000">JUDGING HISTORY TOO QUICKLY</font><br>
<tt>Tue May 27 17:30:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Memorial Day is over, and I received an e-mail from one of you congratulating me on knowing the names cited above.  I replied to him, and will share that reply along with a few other comments:<br><br>
I had help.  I did remember several people (Charlie King was a classmate of mine, and I still have his POW/MIA bracelet; William Pitsenburger had an Aerospace Rescue and Recovery Service troghy for the best PJ section in the world named after him, and we won that trophy when I was in the reserves in Portland).  <br><br>
But we also have The Pararescue Association, and last year they came out with a book entitled &quot;Pararescue, 50 Years, 1943-1993, A Commemorative History&quot; by The Pararescue Association.  They detailed all of these fallen PJs, and their missions.  <br><br>
Two others, whom I did not list, were Steve Northern and Duane Hackney.  Both of these guys survived 'Nam only to die of other causes later.  <br><br>
Steve died in a construction accident (he was decapitated by a wire rope which parted).  He had been in 'Nam for many tours, and when the USAF in its wisdom decided enough was enough (that he couldn't extend again after 3 or 4 extentions), he got out of the service.  Steve was a legend in his own time, and all the PJs from that era would remember him.  He ended up with 30 months in-country and 51 saves.<br><br>
Duane Hackney was with me in Korea and Vietnam (actually, I was with him), and led a charmed life.  He tested the first prototype of a ceramic helmet by bouncing a bullet off it.  Then, in his next tour (while I was in DaNang) he decided that the ceramic helmets were too heavy to wear on our extended flights, and so chose o fiberglass helmet for a rescue mission into Laos.  While on that pickup, a bullet went inside his helmet, clipped his ear, and exited through the fiberglass.  Had it been a ceramic helmet, that bullet would have ricocheted inside the helmet!  Duane, I just found out last fall, died of a heart attack a few years back.<br><br>
Joseph (Teacherguy), I do have a comment on your posting above.  I do not think any of the lives lost in Vietnam were completely &quot;wasted&quot; lives.  The effort does make a difference, and I want those relatives to know that what looks like a waste in the short-term (25 years is not much in history) may yet prove to have been pivital in the history of our nation, and the world, in another 75 years.  We, for the most part, will be gone before we know the entire outcome of the Vietnam War.  I leave you with this thought:<br><br>
&quot;War is an ugly thing,<br>
but not the ugliest of things,<br>
The decayed and degraded state<br>
of moral and patriotic feeling<br>
which thinks that nothing is worth war,<br>
is much worse.<br><br>
&quot;The man who has nothing <br>
for which he is willing to fight,<br>
has no chance of being free,<br>
unless made so by the exertion<br>
of better men than himself.&quot;<br><br>
Author unknown (source: &quot;Pararescue, 50 Years&quot; The Pararescue Association, PO Box 13351, Albuquerque, NM 87192-3351)<br><br>
Take care,<br><br>
John<br>

